    influx_title: 'InfluxDB', influx_sub: 'Select a task.',
    influx_desc: 'InfluxDB is a time-series database. This means it is purpose-built to store data ordered by timestamp (typically sensor readings that come in at regular intervals over time). In the MING stack, InfluxDB is the storage layer. It is preferred because it is optimised for high-speed data ingestion and fast queries on time-based data. Compared to a regular relational database, InfluxDB handles timestamps and large amounts of continuously incoming data much more efficiently. A central concept is measurement, which is a named container for related time-series data, roughly like a table in a SQL database. Examples might be «temperature», «humidity» or «pressure». Each data point has a timestamp (the moment it was recorded, which is the key in a time-series database). InfluxDB also uses retention policies, which are rules that determine how long data is stored. If the policy is set to 30 days, data older than 30 days is automatically deleted — it is not moved to backup or compressed. When you query InfluxDB for for example the last five minutes of temperature data, you get back a time-ordered list of all readings recorded in that time window (not just the current value, and not the entire history). Data is sent from Node-RED to InfluxDB over the network via HTTP, using InfluxDB\'s API. It does not happen via MQTT or direct cable.',
    influx_task1: 'Task 1', influx_task1sub: 'Getting started with InfluxDB.',
