    nodered_title: 'Node-RED', nodered_sub: 'Select a task.',
    nodered_desc: 'Node-RED is a visual programming tool where you build data flows by dragging and connecting nodes graphically, instead of writing code line by line. In the MING stack, Node-RED sits in the middle and acts as the processing layer (meaning it receives raw data, processes it, and sends it on to storage). A flow in Node-RED is a connected sequence of nodes that processes data from input to output. Each node has a specific task, and data flows between them as messages. Node-RED is typically used to add timestamps to data, filter out faulty sensor values, format data into the correct format before storage, route data to different recipients, and trigger alarms when values exceed given limits. This processing level is often called the fog layer (the layer between the sensors and storage or cloud). When Node-RED triggers an alarm based on an incoming value, it is the processing layer working, not storage or visualisation. An important reason Node-RED is needed in the MING stack is that MQTT cannot send data directly to InfluxDB — InfluxDB requires data to be in a specific format (line protocol), and MQTT messages are not in this format. Node-RED therefore receives MQTT messages over the network via TCP/IP, transforms them, and sends them on to InfluxDB.',
    nodered_task1: 'Task 1', nodered_task1sub: 'Getting started with Node-RED.',
