    grafana_title: 'Grafana', grafana_sub: 'Select a task.',
    grafana_desc: 'Grafana is a visualisation tool that can connect to many different data sources and present data as graphs, gauges, tables and heatmaps. In the MING stack, Grafana has one primary role: to visualise data from the database in dashboards. A data source in Grafana is a connection to a database or service that delivers data (for example InfluxDB). It is not a physical sensor or a file that is uploaded manually. The display is built from dashboards and panels, where a dashboard is a collection of several visualisations that together provide an overview, and a panel is a single visualisation in the dashboard. Grafana also has a built-in alerting system that can send emails or messages when a value crosses a defined threshold. Grafana fetches data by sending queries to InfluxDB over the network. It does not subscribe to MQTT and does not read directly from disk. Grafana and InfluxDB work well together because Grafana has built-in support for time-series databases and can plot time series efficiently. For an industrial operator, a dashboard is useful because it gives an overview of multiple process variables in one place (it does not replace the sensors, but makes it possible to monitor the entire process at the same time). When troubleshooting it is important to understand that Grafana only displays data — it does not produce or store it. If a spike appears both in Grafana and in raw data in InfluxDB, the spike originated in the sensor or the measurement itself (not in Grafana or Node-RED). If Grafana shows data from two hours ago even though the sensors are active, the fault is likely that Node-RED is not sending new data to InfluxDB. If an alarm threshold is set but no alarm is triggered, the most likely cause is that the alarm rule is misconfigured or that alerting is not set up correctly.',
